            </div>
            <div class="editorial-byline__rule"></div>
        </div>
    </div>

    <main class="editorial-main">

        <!-- ═══════════════════════════════════════
             PART 1 — THE RIVER
             ═══════════════════════════════════════ -->

        <article class="editorial-article" data-reveal>
            <p class="editorial-lede">
                On a Tuesday morning in late September, Brett Seng stands knee-deep in the Gallatin River, reading water the way most people read faces. The riffles say one thing, the foam line another, and the dark seam where current meets slack tells him everything he needs to know about where a brown trout is holding, and why. He has been doing this for twenty-three years. Long enough that the reading has become a kind of fluency, the way a musician stops seeing notes and simply hears music.
            </p>
        </article>

        <article class="editorial-article" data-reveal>
            <p>
                The valley is quiet in the way only Montana can manage. Not silent&mdash;the river talks constantly, a low static braided with birdsong and the occasional crack of a twig in the willows&mdash;but quiet in the sense that no one is asking anything of anyone. Upstream, the Gallatin Range shoulders into a sky the color of clean slate. Downstream, cottonwoods are just beginning their turn, the first yellows appearing like match strikes in a wall of green. The air smells of sage and cold water and the faintest sweetness of decaying leaves.
            </p>
        </article>

        <!-- FULL-BLEED IMAGE -->
        <figure class="editorial-fullbleed" data-reveal>
            <Image
                src={goldenMeadow}
                alt="A golden meadow stretches toward a winding river, the grass catching late-afternoon light"
                class="editorial-fullbleed__img"
                widths={[600, 1200, 2000]}
                sizes="100vw"
                quality={82}
                format="webp"
                loading="lazy"
            />
            <figcaption class="editorial-caption">The Gallatin Valley in September. The meadows go gold weeks before the cottonwoods follow.</figcaption>
        </figure>

        <article class="editorial-article" data-reveal>
            <p>
                Seng strips line from his reel with the unhurried economy of someone who has made this cast ten thousand times. The loop unfurls, the fly settles into the film like a period at the end of a sentence, and the drift begins. He is not performing. There is no audience here except the osprey circling above the riffle and whatever is finning in the shadow of that submerged boulder. This is simply what he does. What he has always done.
            </p>
            <p>
                It is tempting to call this a simple life, but that would be a mistake. Simple implies easy. What Seng has built over more than two decades as a fly fishing guide and licensed outfitter in southwest Montana is something more nuanced than that. It is a life stripped to its essentials&mdash;river, weather, client, trout&mdash;but each of those essentials contains a universe of variables. Knowing which river to fish on which day, reading the mood of a nervous first-timer versus the impatience of a seasoned angler, understanding that the same stretch of the Madison fishes entirely differently in June than it does in October. This is complex work dressed in waders and a sun-faded cap.
            </p>
        </article>

        <!-- SECTION BREAK -->
        <div class="editorial-ornament" data-reveal>&bull;&ensp;&bull;&ensp;&bull;</div>

        <!-- ═══════════════════════════════════════
             PART 2 — THE GUIDE
             ═══════════════════════════════════════ -->

        <article class="editorial-article" data-reveal>
            <h2 class="editorial-section-label">The Guide</h2>
            <h3 class="editorial-section-heading">A Gentleman's<br/>Dirtbag Club</h3>
        </article>

        <!-- INSET IMAGE — RIGHT -->
        <article class="editorial-article editorial-article--with-inset" data-reveal>
            <figure class="editorial-inset editorial-inset--right">
                <Image
                    src={brettPhoto}
                    alt="Brett Seng on the river, relaxed and sun-weathered, the mountains at his back"
                    class="editorial-inset__img"
                    widths={[400, 800]}
                    sizes="(max-width: 768px) 100vw, 340px"
                    quality={82}
                    format="webp"
                    loading="lazy"
                />
                <figcaption class="editorial-caption">Brett Seng, outfitter and owner of Roam Outfitters, on the water in the Gallatin Valley.</figcaption>
            </figure>
            <p>
                Brett Seng did not grow up dreaming of corner offices. He grew up dreaming of corner pools&mdash;the deep, shaded bends where currents converge and big fish wait with the patience of monks. He started guiding at twenty, an age when most people are still figuring out what they want from life. He already knew. The rivers of Montana had answered every question he thought to ask, and most of the ones he hadn't.
            </p>
            <p>
                In 2013, after more than a decade of guiding under other outfitters, he earned his outfitter license and launched Roam Outfitters. The name was deliberate. "Roam" is not just a brand word&mdash;it is a philosophy of angling that prizes exploration over routine, curiosity over habit. Where some guides build a career around a single stretch of a single river, Seng built his around range. From spring creeks to freestone rivers, tailwaters to mountain lakes, the breadth of water he covers is uncommon in a profession that tends toward specialization.
            </p>
            <p>
                His tagline, "A Gentleman's Dirtbag Club," captures the contradiction at the heart of his operation. The gear is first-rate&mdash;Orvis rods, Lamson reels, custom-tied flies&mdash;and the lunch spread on a full-day float would not embarrass a good restaurant. But the man behind it all is just as happy sleeping in his truck at a put-in, waking before dawn to watch the river come alive. Refinement without pretension. Craft without ego.
            </p>
        </article>

        <!-- FULL-BLEED IMAGE -->
        <figure class="editorial-fullbleed" data-reveal>
            <Image
                src={selectingFlies}
                alt="A close view of a fly box open beside the river, dozens of hand-tied flies arranged in neat rows"
                class="editorial-fullbleed__img"
                widths={[600, 1200, 2000]}
                sizes="100vw"
                quality={82}
                format="webp"
                loading="lazy"
