            <figcaption class="editorial-caption">The fly box as autobiography. Two decades of patterns, each one tied to a specific hatch, a specific river, a specific memory.</figcaption>
        </figure>

        <article class="editorial-article" data-reveal>
            <p>
                What sets Seng apart, his clients will tell you, is the customization. He does not run a template trip. Every day on the water is built around the people in the boat&mdash;their skill level, their ambitions, their temperament. A father bringing his twelve-year-old for a first time will fish different water than a couple of experienced anglers chasing trophy browns. "I want people to feel like this trip was made for them," he says, "because it was."
            </p>
            <p>
                There is a particular kind of trust that forms between a guide and a client over the course of a long day on the river. You are, in a real sense, putting your experience in someone else's hands. Seng takes that seriously. He reads his clients the way he reads water&mdash;patiently, carefully, always looking for what's happening beneath the surface.
            </p>
        </article>

        <!-- SECTION BREAK -->
        <div class="editorial-ornament" data-reveal>&bull;&ensp;&bull;&ensp;&bull;</div>

        <!-- ═══════════════════════════════════════
             PART 3 — THE WATERS
             ═══════════════════════════════════════ -->

        <article class="editorial-article" data-reveal>
            <h2 class="editorial-section-label">The Waters</h2>
            <h3 class="editorial-section-heading">Six Rivers,<br/>One Valley</h3>
        </article>

        <article class="editorial-article" data-reveal>
            <p class="editorial-drop-cap">
                The Gallatin is his home water, the river he knows the way you know the streets of the town where you grew up&mdash;every turn memorized, every shortcut catalogued, but still capable of surprising you on any given day. It runs cold and fast out of Yellowstone National Park, threading through the canyon that bears its name before opening into the valley south of Bozeman. In summer, the Gallatin is a caddis factory, its riffles boiling with hatches that bring trout to the surface in feeding frenzies that can turn a mediocre caster into a hero. In autumn, the browns move upstream to spawn, and the river takes on a different character entirely&mdash;slower, deeper, more secretive.
            </p>
        </article>

        <!-- FULL-BLEED IMAGE -->
        <figure class="editorial-fullbleed" data-reveal>
            <Image
                src={gallatinCanyon}
                alt="The Gallatin River cuts through its canyon, steep forested walls rising on either side"
                class="editorial-fullbleed__img"
                widths={[600, 1200, 2000]}
                sizes="100vw"
                quality={82}
                format="webp"
                loading="lazy"
            />
            <figcaption class="editorial-caption">Gallatin Canyon. The river drops nearly two thousand feet between Yellowstone and the valley floor.</figcaption>
        </figure>

        <article class="editorial-article" data-reveal>
            <p>
                The Yellowstone is the big river, the drama. America's longest undammed river enters Montana through Paradise Valley like a headline, wide and muscular, full of the kind of water that makes you reconsider your tackle. Its cutthroat and rainbow populations are the stuff of regional legend, and floating the Yellowstone in a drift boat on a cloudless July day is one of those experiences that recalibrates your understanding of what a river can be.
            </p>
            <p>
                The Madison is the workhorse&mdash;fifty miles of trout water between Quake Lake and Ennis that fishes well in every month of the open season. It is one of the most famous trout streams in the world, and for good reason: the Madison delivers. Rainbows and browns in honest numbers, in honest sizes, on water that rewards both technical skill and raw enthusiasm.
            </p>
        </article>

        <!-- INSET IMAGE — LEFT -->
        <article class="editorial-article editorial-article--with-inset" data-reveal>
            <figure class="editorial-inset editorial-inset--left">
                <Image
                    src={wadeFishing}
                    alt="An angler wade-fishes a canyon stretch, the river framed by towering rock walls"
                    class="editorial-inset__img"
                    widths={[400, 800]}
                    sizes="(max-width: 768px) 100vw, 340px"
                    quality={82}
                    format="webp"
                    loading="lazy"
                />
                <figcaption class="editorial-caption">Walk-wade fishing in a canyon stretch. Some of the best water is only accessible on foot.</figcaption>
            </figure>
            <p>
                The Jefferson is quieter, less celebrated, and that is precisely its appeal. It meanders through ranch country with the unhurried patience of a river that has nothing to prove. The Jefferson is where Seng takes clients who want solitude more than spectacle&mdash;the kind of people who measure a day not by fish count but by the number of other boats they didn't see.
            </p>
            <p>
                The Boulder is the wild card, a smaller freestone river that fishes above its weight class. Its canyon sections offer pocket water that rewards the angler willing to work for each fish&mdash;short casts, quick mends, and the particular satisfaction of fooling a trout in water so clear that every refusal happens in full view.
            </p>
            <p>
                And then there is the Missouri, the big tailwater south of Helena, which Seng calls "the graduate seminar." The Missouri below Holter Dam is one of the finest technical dry-fly fisheries in North America. The fish are educated, the hatches are predictable but demanding, and the rewards for getting it right are extraordinary. A twenty-inch rainbow on a size-18 pale morning dun is a memory that does not fade.
            </p>
        </article>

        <!-- PULL QUOTE -->
        <aside class="editorial-pullquote" data-reveal>
            <div class="editorial-pullquote__mark">&ldquo;</div>
            <blockquote class="editorial-pullquote__text">
                I never wanted the corner office. I wanted the corner pool on the bend of the Gallatin where the browns stack up in October.
            </blockquote>
        </aside>

        <!-- FULL-BLEED IMAGE -->
