        <!-- ═══════════════════════════════════════
             PART 4 — THE FAMILY
             ═══════════════════════════════════════ -->

        <article class="editorial-article" data-reveal>
            <h2 class="editorial-section-label">The Family</h2>
            <h3 class="editorial-section-heading">What the<br/>River Gives Back</h3>
        </article>

        <article class="editorial-article" data-reveal>
            <p class="editorial-drop-cap">
                There is a photograph on Seng's phone that he shows to almost no one, and yet it might be the most important image he has ever taken. It is of his son, Waylon, holding a brown trout in a small creek behind their house. The fish is maybe eight inches long. Waylon is grinning so hard his face looks like it might split in two. It is not, by any objective measure, a remarkable photograph. But it contains, in a single frame, everything Seng has worked twenty-three years to build.
            </p>
        </article>

        <!-- TWO-UP IMAGES -->
        <div class="editorial-two-up" data-reveal>
            <figure class="editorial-two-up__fig">
                <Image
                    src={brettSonBrown}
                    alt="Brett and his son Waylon with a brown trout, both beaming at the camera"
                    class="editorial-two-up__img"
                    widths={[400, 800]}
                    sizes="(max-width: 768px) 100vw, 50vw"
                    quality={82}
                    format="webp"
                    loading="lazy"
                />
                <figcaption class="editorial-caption">Waylon with a brown trout. The grin tells the whole story.</figcaption>
            </figure>
            <figure class="editorial-two-up__fig">
                <Image
                    src={brettDaughterCreek}
                    alt="Brett's daughter Letty holds a fish at a creek, delighted and proud"
                    class="editorial-two-up__img"
                    widths={[400, 800]}
                    sizes="(max-width: 768px) 100vw, 50vw"
                    quality={82}
                    format="webp"
                    loading="lazy"
                />
                <figcaption class="editorial-caption">Letty at the creek. She is already developing her own theories about where the fish hold.</figcaption>
            </figure>
        </div>

        <article class="editorial-article" data-reveal>
            <p>
                His wife, Ally, is the infrastructure that makes the whole enterprise possible. While Brett is on the water six days a week during the high season, she is managing the household, raising two children who are growing up steeped in river culture, and tolerating the particular brand of chaos that comes with being married to someone whose office has no walls. "She's the reason any of this works," Seng says, and it is one of the few times in conversation that the laconic guide sounds truly emphatic.
            </p>
            <p>
                Waylon and Letty are being raised on the water in a way that has become increasingly rare. They know the names of mayflies before they know the names of state capitals. They can identify a rising trout from fifty yards. They are growing up with the understanding that a good life does not require a large house or a prestigious title&mdash;it requires attention, patience, and a willingness to stand in cold water at first light because the river is doing something interesting.
            </p>
        </article>

        <!-- PULL QUOTE -->
