        <!-- ═══════════════════════════════════════
             PART 5 — THE TRIP
             ═══════════════════════════════════════ -->

        <article class="editorial-article" data-reveal>
            <h2 class="editorial-section-label">The Trip</h2>
            <h3 class="editorial-section-heading">Your Day<br/>on the Water</h3>
        </article>

        <article class="editorial-article" data-reveal>
            <p>
                If you have read this far, you are probably thinking about booking a trip. Here is what that looks like. You call Brett. You talk about what you want&mdash;a full day or a half, float or walk-and-wade, big water or small, dry flies or nymphs, trophy hunt or numbers game. He listens. He asks a few questions. Then he builds a day around your answers.
            </p>
            <p>
                Full days run eight hours on the water, with a streamside lunch that has become something of a local legend. Half days are four to five hours, perfect for mornings or evenings when the hatches are best. Float trips accommodate up to two anglers; walk-and-wade trips can take three. Every trip includes Orvis rods, Lamson reels, custom flies, and waders if you need them. You bring a fishing license, sunglasses, and whatever optimism you can muster at five in the morning.
            </p>
        </article>

        <!-- TRIP DETAILS SIDEBAR -->
